{"id":"2105.12282","submitter":"EPTCS","authors":"Sophie Libkind, Andrew Baas, Evan Patterson, James Fairbanks","title":"Operadic Modeling of Dynamical Systems: Mathematics and Computation","comments":"In Proceedings ACT 2021, arXiv:2211.01102","journal-ref":"EPTCS 372, 2022, pp. 192-206","doi":"10.4204/EPTCS.372.14","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Dynamical systems are ubiquitous in science and engineering as models of\nphenomena that evolve over time. Although complex dynamical systems tend to\nhave important modular structure, conventional modeling approaches suppress\nthis structure. Building on recent work in applied category theory, we show how\ndeterministic dynamical systems, discrete and continuous, can be composed in a\nhierarchical style. In mathematical terms, we reformulate some existing operads\nof wiring diagrams and introduce new ones, using the general formalism of\nC-sets (copresheaves). We then establish dynamical systems as algebras of these\noperads. In a computational vein, we show that Euler's method is functorial for\nundirected systems, extending a previous result for directed systems. All of\nthe ideas in this paper are implemented as practical software using Catlab and\nthe AlgebraicJulia ecosystem, written in the Julia programming language for\nscientific computing.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 26 May 2021 01:03:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 28 May 2021 05:06:07 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 3 Nov 2022 14:09:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-04"}
